  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks established to combat money laundering. The primary organization leading this effort is the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which was established in 1989 by the G7 countries. The FATF sets international standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. These standards are recognized and implemented by its member countries and other jurisdictions around the world.\n\n### Key International Frameworks:\n1. **FATF Recommendations**:\n   - The **Forty Recommendations** provide a comprehensive set of measures for countries to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - The **Nine Special Recommendations** focus specifically on terrorist financing (though some have been integrated into the updated Forty Recommendations).\n   - The FATF regularly updates these recommendations to address emerging risks, such as virtual assets and digital currencies.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**:\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)**: Includes provisions to combat money laundering.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC)**: Requires member states to establish measures to prevent and combat money laundering related to corruption.\n\n3. **Egmont Group**:\n   - An international network of Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) that facilitates the exchange of financial intelligence to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - Provides guidelines for banks to implement effective AML measures, including customer due diligence and risk management.\n\n5. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has implemented several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs)** that require member states to adopt measures to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing. The **6th AMLD** (2020) strengthened criminal penalties and expanded the scope of predicate offenses.\n\n### Implementation:\nCountries are expected to implement these international standards into their national laws and regulations. The FATF conducts mutual evaluations to assess how well countries are adhering to these standards and publishes reports on their compliance.\n\n### Enforcement:\nWhile there is no global enforcement body, non-compliance with FATF standards can result in countries being placed on the **FATF Grey List** (increased monitoring) or **Black List** (high-risk jurisdictions), which can lead to economic sanctions, reputational damage, and restricted access to international financial systems.\n\nIn summary, international laws and frameworks against money laundering are robust and continuously evolving to address new challenges in the global financial system.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
